<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF107-925-120  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 925 120.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computergram International  Nov 30 1989 n1316* Full Text COPYRIGHT Apt Data Services 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Microcontrollers grow MIPS as Microchip offers 8bit RISC parts.andO;(Microchip Technology Inc.; reduced-instruction-set computer)(product announcement)andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT>Company:   Microchip Technology Inc. (product introduction).andO;Product:   Microchip Technology PIC16C54 (Controller) (product introduction)Microchip Technology PIC16C55 (Controller) (product introduction).andO;Topic:     Product IntroductionReduced-Instruction-Set ComputersControllersMicroelectronicsApplications.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>MICROCONTROLLERS GROW MIPS AS MICROCHIPandM;OFFERS 8BIR RISC PARTSandM;In the bargain-basement microprocessor department, few parts have been morecheap and cheerful than microcontrollers, those simple computers on a chipthat do anything from managing your washing machine program to timing thecarburettor in your car - and are also widely used in simple computerperipheral control applications.andP;  But Chandler, Arizona-based MicrochipTechnology Inc is set to make designers look at microcontrollers in a wholenew light with the introduction of a pair of 8-bit RISC microcontrollers thatit rates at 5 MIPS.andP;  The two variants are an EpROM and a one-timeprogrammable version of the basic CMOS part, which includes 32 8-bitregisters, a 16-bit timer-counter, a watchdog timer for when the parts areused in battery-driven devices, and an on-chip oscillator.andP;  The 18-pinPIC16C54 is $2.40 for 2,500-up, the 28-pin PIC16C55 is $2.95 in the samequantity, and the parts are shipping in volume now.andP;  The Pic Pak assemblerand software simulator is $500, and Microindustrie of San Diego has a PicesIII package, including an in-circuit emulator that plugs into a prototype forreal-time emulation and symbolic debug at up to 20MHz.andP;  The package sells for$2,000.andO;</TEXT></DOC>